# 📌 Steps to Upload Django Project on GitHub
# 1. Go to Your Project Folder

# Suppose your project is inside:

# ~/Desktop/INT253_DJANGO/FirstProject/


# This folder contains:

# venv/
# first/
# myapp/
# manage.py


# 👉 Open Terminal here.

# 2. Initialize Git
# git init

# 3. Create a .gitignore File

# Very important 🚨 — you should NOT upload your virtual environment (venv) or compiled files.

# Create a file named .gitignore in your project root:

# venv/
# __pycache__/
# *.pyc
# *.sqlite3
# .env

# 4. Add All Files
# git add .

# 5. Commit Changes
# git commit -m "Initial commit - First Django Project"

# 6. Create a New GitHub Repository

# Go to GitHub
#  → New Repository.

# Name it (example: FirstProject).

# Don’t add README or .gitignore (you already have one).

# Copy the repo URL (e.g. https://github.com/yourusername/FirstProject.git).

# 7. Link Local Project to GitHub Repo
# git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/FirstProject.git

# 8. Push Code
# git branch -M main
# git push -u origin main


# ✅ Now your Django project is uploaded to GitHub!

# 📌 Best Practice for Multiple Projects

# If you have:

# ~/Desktop/INT253_DJANGO/
#    ├── FirstProject/
#    ├── SecondProject/
#    ├── ThirdProject/


# 👉 Create separate GitHub repos for each project.
# So:

# FirstProject → GitHub repo FirstProject

# SecondProject → GitHub repo SecondProject

# This way, each project has its own version history.

# ⚡ Pro Tip: You can also use GitHub Desktop if you prefer GUI instead of command line.